1
00:00:02,242 --> 00:00:04,104
I just want to say a few things about hindrances.

2
00:00:08,429 --> 00:00:12,695
First of all, we mustn't confuse hindrances with the moral law.

3
00:00:13,275 --> 00:00:25,853
You know, these precepts that we take which are basically guides to how to stop creating problems for ourselves through doing harm and lies and all that.

4
00:00:27,754 --> 00:00:32,180
These hindrances are the products of more than just...

5
00:00:32,970 --> 00:00:40,658
our problem with moral behavior, they arise because of our past conditioning.

6
00:00:43,341 --> 00:00:46,183
So they arise because of what's called sankhara.

7
00:00:46,884 --> 00:00:52,551
Sankhara is translated as dispositions, attitudes.

8
00:00:54,512 --> 00:01:00,057
And they're actually created by our own will, by our own decision making.

9
00:01:01,826 --> 00:01:30,855
So, these sankharas are actually made by an act of will and what we've ended up with is a whole set of dispositions which put all together

10
00:01:31,897 --> 00:01:35,962
comes down to our personalities, our character, personalities and character.

11
00:01:38,506 --> 00:01:52,144
And when we sit in meditation, what we come across, most of the time anyway, is all the bad stuff, all the unfortunate conditionings that we've given ourselves.

12
00:01:52,164 --> 00:02:01,094
So the Buddha split these up into five sections, which makes it fairly easy for us to discuss and to see what we can do about it.

13
00:02:02,644 --> 00:02:12,495
So remember the process of meditation, part of it, I mean in a sense most of the work is concerned with purifying the sankhara, purifying the heart.

14
00:02:14,015 --> 00:02:24,526
In fact the opening of the Satipaṭṭhāna discourse, the discourse on how to establish awareness the first thing he says is for the purification of beings.

15
00:02:25,768 --> 00:02:30,372
That's the first reason for practicing this meditation for the purification of beings.

16
00:02:30,707 --> 00:02:34,192
Only at the end of the line is it for attaining the end of suffering.

17
00:02:34,693 --> 00:02:44,424
So there's a recognition there that the process is one of purifying the heart of all these negativities, these turbulences.

18
00:02:46,347 --> 00:02:54,336
So the first one is all to do with indulgence, all to do with our relationship to pleasure.

19
00:02:58,230 --> 00:03:01,899
So that normally comes out when we're sitting in all sorts of fantasies, you know.

20
00:03:03,140 --> 00:03:04,544
Sex, drugs, rock and roll.

21
00:03:05,967 --> 00:03:06,829
Taking holidays.

22
00:03:07,830 --> 00:03:08,431
Making money.

23
00:03:09,915 --> 00:03:10,796
Becoming famous.

24
00:03:11,778 --> 00:03:12,280
Status.

25
00:03:13,883 --> 00:03:14,264
Power.

26
00:03:15,187 --> 00:03:17,792
And all those lovely dreams we have about power.

27
00:03:19,408 --> 00:03:25,920
So those are the four worldly pursuits of getting the rich, the powerful and the famous.

28
00:03:26,020 --> 00:03:26,883
I mean, we have it, you see.

29
00:03:26,923 --> 00:03:28,104
The rich, the powerful and the famous.

30
00:03:28,665 --> 00:03:31,151
And the fourth one is seeking pleasure.

31
00:03:32,753 --> 00:03:35,699
So our society is especially bent on that last one.

32
00:03:37,062 --> 00:03:41,669
That's why we have a general problem with obsession and addiction.

33
00:03:44,097 --> 00:04:02,442
So now in meditation, when we sit, you see, this conditioning, this wanting to enjoy life, this wanting to enjoy life in one of those categories, getting rich, getting powerful and all that, that desire of seeking happiness there, booms up, doesn't it?

34
00:04:02,461 --> 00:04:04,064
Suddenly we're lost in all these dreams.

35
00:04:06,168 --> 00:04:09,032
All these fantasies come up, just take us away from the meditation.

36
00:04:11,074 --> 00:04:12,956
Sort of creating a virtual reality.

37
00:04:15,198 --> 00:04:16,680
I mean, while we're in there, it's great.

38
00:04:17,661 --> 00:04:22,326
It's only when we wake up and we realize it's not true that it hurts.

39
00:04:25,069 --> 00:04:27,552
So, what can we do, you see?

40
00:04:28,952 --> 00:04:34,298
Well, the first thing to really grasp, the first thing to really grasp is that you can't do anything.

41
00:04:35,300 --> 00:04:43,990
So once you recognize that, once you recognize that we are having created this conditioning, we can't do anything about it.

42
00:04:45,944 --> 00:04:53,471
Once you recognize that, then that releases us from all effort to try and change the mind, to try and change the heart.

43
00:04:55,533 --> 00:04:56,413
Which is a relief, isn't it?

44
00:04:56,954 --> 00:04:57,514
In one sense.

45
00:04:58,314 --> 00:05:02,059
If you know you can't do anything about something, then you just accept it.

46
00:05:02,079 --> 00:05:02,838
This is the way it is.

47
00:05:06,543 --> 00:05:14,290
So, having recognized that it's a conditioning in the heart, it's like you set the car in gear or something and you're off.

48
00:05:14,670 --> 00:05:15,951
You've created a momentum

49
00:05:17,095 --> 00:05:27,509
It doesn't matter what you do, you can stomp on the brake as much as you want, but the car has a momentum, it has to, as it were, exhaust that momentum.

50
00:05:29,052 --> 00:05:42,951
So, in meditation, when all these dreams come up, you see, and you recognize, well, I can't do anything about this turbulence, I can't do anything about this momentum, then the option is to jump out of that system.

51
00:05:44,584 --> 00:05:47,735
And when you jump out of the system, you become its observer.

52
00:05:47,976 --> 00:05:49,180
You become its knower.

53
00:05:49,862 --> 00:05:53,696
In which case, this turbulence, what can it do?

54
00:05:54,740 --> 00:05:56,264
It has to expend its energy.

55
00:05:59,148 --> 00:06:19,187
So, just as we've created this energy, just as we've created this turbulence through our acts of will to indulge, you see, by withdrawing that will, which is the empowerment of that, by withdrawing that will, it now is just left to itself, in which case it can't grow and it has to exhaust itself.

56
00:06:20,807 --> 00:06:28,074
So, in our meditation, when we find ourselves wandering away, you see, we just note what's happened and we come back.

57
00:06:28,747 --> 00:06:29,608
And that's the practice.

58
00:06:29,889 --> 00:06:31,634
We just know what's happened, and we come back.

59
00:06:32,334 --> 00:06:34,922
We don't know what's happened and say, oh, that's good, I'll get into that.

60
00:06:35,702 --> 00:06:37,427
See, in this case, we'd be off again.

61
00:06:37,928 --> 00:06:39,492
We'd be creating the wheel, you see.

62
00:06:40,033 --> 00:06:46,148
We just know, off on dreaming, some sort of fantasy, whatever it is, acknowledge it, and we come back.

63
00:06:47,156 --> 00:06:58,153
If you can actually come back to a feeling of a longing, of a real strong desire, then you're really at what's motivating all these dreams.

64
00:06:58,574 --> 00:07:10,052
And just by staying with the feeling, as you might feel it in the heart, in the chest especially, you see, then you just stay with that and you can actually begin to feel that it's giving up, it's giving away, you see.

65
00:07:10,612 --> 00:07:12,995
And that gives you confidence that in fact...

66
00:07:13,617 --> 00:07:19,365
By simply not doing anything, the system will find its own equilibrium.

67
00:07:21,247 --> 00:07:26,076
So if you stir up water, you see, and you take the paddle out, what happens?

68
00:07:27,016 --> 00:07:29,199
It goes round a bit and then it stops.

69
00:07:29,220 --> 00:07:30,603
So it's exactly the same with the mind.

70
00:07:31,764 --> 00:07:35,209
It's only an energy system and it just needs that continual empowerment.

71
00:07:36,672 --> 00:07:42,240
So once you opt out of empowering that, then you'll see the mind just becomes more and more quiet.

72
00:07:44,752 --> 00:07:45,983
It takes a long time, that's all.

73
00:07:46,911 --> 00:07:48,889
There's a lot of conditioning there.

74
00:07:54,151 --> 00:08:04,305
Even though we sometimes wander off on these fantasies, we can say that, unwittingly, there is a small act of will there, but it's not such an empowering one.

75
00:08:04,725 --> 00:08:07,350
And eventually, the system will quieten down.

76
00:08:07,971 --> 00:08:19,887
Now, you have to really make an effort on that, and what you find is, of course, is that you sit with good intent, but when something comes up, you know, like, you want to set up a business or something, or you want to...

77
00:08:20,358 --> 00:08:26,286
you want to get on with this job, or you've got that shed to paint, you know.

78
00:08:26,526 --> 00:08:31,733
And then you like to think about that, you know, get it worked out, are you going to do it, you see.

79
00:08:32,094 --> 00:08:41,446
And although you're saying to yourself, you know, dreaming, dreaming, and before you know it, you're off, you see.

80
00:08:42,187 --> 00:08:46,753
Because you haven't made that really strong act of determination to withstand it, you see.

81
00:08:48,285 --> 00:08:49,248
So it's got to be stronger.

82
00:08:49,628 --> 00:08:54,436
And it's no excuse, you see, if after the meditation you say to yourself, well, that was absolutely useless.

83
00:08:54,576 --> 00:08:58,984
It's only useless because you didn't make the right decision.

84
00:08:59,104 --> 00:09:08,278
So if we're going to judge our meditation, and we can do to a certain level, you see, we can actually say to ourselves, well, you know, I should have been stronger there.

85
00:09:08,318 --> 00:09:14,850
I should have made that decision not to indulge in that particular dream or fantasy.

86
00:09:15,488 --> 00:09:22,682
And then recognizing that fault, you see, one makes the determination, right, next time I'll stay with it, you see.

87
00:09:27,772 --> 00:09:37,951
So that's all you can do with desire, you see, and we're up against it when we eat, you see, so we can see the power of it, the power of desire.

88
00:09:39,316 --> 00:09:42,000
Remember that a lot of desire has a neurotic base.

89
00:09:43,081 --> 00:09:45,605
Meaning that it's not just a simple desire.

90
00:09:45,686 --> 00:09:47,307
It's not just a desire for pleasure.

91
00:09:47,327 --> 00:09:51,794
There's underneath it a desire for escape from the suffering that it's hiding.

92
00:09:53,517 --> 00:09:55,520
I mean, take a very simple one like boredom.

93
00:09:57,062 --> 00:09:58,225
You can't handle boredom.

94
00:09:58,284 --> 00:09:59,586
You can't handle loneliness.

95
00:10:01,188 --> 00:10:02,250
So off you go, you see.

96
00:10:03,011 --> 00:10:05,294
Turn the TV on, call a friend up, tell them how bored you are.

97
00:10:05,696 --> 00:10:06,437
Things like that.

98
00:10:07,462 --> 00:10:08,904
You're always shooting off.

99
00:10:08,924 --> 00:10:15,315
So what seems to be on the surface a search for happiness is actually an escape.

100
00:10:16,917 --> 00:10:22,565
And hence we get into that sort of neurotic area where what we're doing is actually a metaphor.

101
00:10:22,966 --> 00:10:26,490
It's actually a metaphor for that neurosis.

102
00:10:26,831 --> 00:10:33,841
So food is a very obvious place where really we're just feeding ourselves with love.

103
00:10:35,154 --> 00:10:37,937
We need to be loved and nobody loves us and we can't handle it.

104
00:10:38,678 --> 00:10:40,881
So we've got to eat and feel better.

105
00:10:43,445 --> 00:10:44,265
Or you feel anxious.

106
00:10:44,326 --> 00:10:45,567
You feel anxious about life.

107
00:10:45,807 --> 00:10:47,149
It's in the stomach anxiety, isn't it?

108
00:10:47,188 --> 00:10:49,250
So you eat and it feels good.

109
00:10:50,413 --> 00:10:50,633
See?

110
00:10:52,475 --> 00:10:56,639
Which doesn't mean to say that you can't turn out to be an enormously wonderful chef.

111
00:10:57,024 --> 00:11:00,974
You can still be a fantastic artist in cooking, but it's covering up this.

112
00:11:02,177 --> 00:11:04,061
And that's one of the reasons for renunciation.

113
00:11:04,322 --> 00:11:14,645
That's why the Buddha constantly asks us to renounce things, to renounce those pleasures, because often when we give something up we like, then we see this underbelly of dissatisfaction.

114
00:11:21,442 --> 00:11:24,505
Which is not the same as self-mortification.

115
00:11:25,366 --> 00:11:34,577
You know, these words, it depends how you define them, obviously, but self-mortification is a sort of wrong understanding that in order to become saintly, we have to suffer.

116
00:11:36,259 --> 00:11:41,144
You beat yourself up and hang yourself by your fingers from a tree or something.

117
00:11:41,164 --> 00:11:42,106
So that really hurts.

118
00:11:42,726 --> 00:11:45,190
And this creates an enormous piety.

119
00:11:46,317 --> 00:11:47,217
All it does, it hurts.

120
00:11:47,958 --> 00:11:48,980
It doesn't do anything at all.

121
00:11:49,679 --> 00:11:52,023
So renunciation is something different.

122
00:11:52,043 --> 00:11:57,788
Renunciation is giving something up in order to feel the attachment, see the attachment that we have to things.

123
00:12:06,918 --> 00:12:08,139
So that's the first hindrance.

124
00:12:08,219 --> 00:12:09,980
The next one is all to do with aversion.

125
00:12:10,902 --> 00:12:11,962
It's all to do with anger.

126
00:12:12,663 --> 00:12:13,945
Boredom is part of it.

127
00:12:14,784 --> 00:12:18,653
Even parts of our depression can sort of be that too.

128
00:12:19,375 --> 00:12:26,450
Now, the rather good thing about aversion is, of course, it doesn't like its object.

129
00:12:27,110 --> 00:12:34,025
And therefore, in a sort of rather helpful way, it creates a distance for us immediately.

130
00:12:34,005 --> 00:12:41,947
So if you're sitting at home and somebody plays music next door that you don't like, you see, then immediately you push it away, you see.

131
00:12:42,148 --> 00:12:46,158
So you're right in contact with what it is that's annoying you.

132
00:12:46,611 --> 00:12:54,129
Unlike indulgence, where you become it, you become the cornflakes, in this case you want to dissociate.

133
00:12:54,811 --> 00:12:59,662
So that's a great help for us, you see, because at least that stops us indulging in the object.

134
00:12:59,761 --> 00:13:05,193
But we now indulge in this hatred, we now indulge in this anger, irritation, whatever it is.

135
00:13:06,607 --> 00:13:13,981
So whenever that arises in the mind, because of a memory, etc., you have to be very careful to stay with the feeling of it.

136
00:13:14,341 --> 00:13:17,408
You have to allow that also to burn out.

137
00:13:17,609 --> 00:13:18,671
So it's always the same.

138
00:13:18,951 --> 00:13:26,946
It's always the same technique of coming off the mind with its imaginations and feeling the feeling.

139
00:13:27,634 --> 00:13:28,615
See?

140
00:13:28,816 --> 00:13:37,445
That's a tautology, to feel the feeling, but it's surprising how we don't actually feel things properly and fully in their real nature.

141
00:13:38,306 --> 00:13:52,899
And the Buddha obviously had a hard time getting people to do this as well, because in the discourse on how to establish mindfulness, he also repeats it, vedana vedanupasiti, to see feeling in feeling, or to see feeling as feeling.

142
00:13:52,879 --> 00:14:11,663
He's sort of stretching the language to try and get people to see that they've got to go underneath the mind, underneath thought, underneath opinion and idea, and to get down to the raw feeling itself, which is felt as a feeling in the body, isn't it?

143
00:14:11,903 --> 00:14:14,466
Anger, it's a burning, you see, or whatever.

144
00:14:17,585 --> 00:14:21,330
The other side of that is fear, of course, and anxiety.

145
00:14:21,530 --> 00:14:22,792
See, that's also an aversion.

146
00:14:22,851 --> 00:14:23,673
That's running away.

147
00:14:23,693 --> 00:14:25,375
So again, it's the same thing.

148
00:14:25,576 --> 00:14:27,077
You've got to get into the body.

149
00:14:27,097 --> 00:14:28,220
You've got to feel it, you see.

150
00:14:28,600 --> 00:14:34,128
Now, when you get into these sorts of things, again, you find yourself in a relationship.

151
00:14:34,948 --> 00:14:38,313
When something is burning inside you, again, you don't like it, you see.

152
00:14:38,453 --> 00:14:40,437
So there's an aversion to the aversion.

153
00:14:41,446 --> 00:14:48,115
So you've got to observe that too, you've got to observe the not wanting to feel anger, not wanting to feel boredom.

154
00:14:50,578 --> 00:14:58,711
So recognizing that, again you don't push it away, you just know that that's there, that's happening, and you just sit quietly with the feelings.

155
00:15:00,052 --> 00:15:04,399
See it more as a process, something changing, become interested in it as a process.

156
00:15:06,217 --> 00:15:07,861
See, same with anxiety.

157
00:15:08,043 --> 00:15:16,864
See, instead of shooting off getting anxious about being anxious, being fearful of fear, and then, you know, we find ourselves off on some sort of mental trip.

158
00:15:17,304 --> 00:15:20,413
See, get used to feeling the feelings of fear.

159
00:15:23,346 --> 00:15:24,850
It doesn't take that much.

160
00:15:25,672 --> 00:15:26,653
Just to stay with them.

161
00:15:27,375 --> 00:15:29,759
Pass the mind around where you feel it.

162
00:15:30,301 --> 00:15:32,785
Pass the attention across it and up it.

163
00:15:33,126 --> 00:15:33,869
Penetrate it.

164
00:15:33,969 --> 00:15:35,251
Come in and out of it.

165
00:15:35,591 --> 00:15:36,695
See it as a process.

166
00:15:38,477 --> 00:15:44,190
Find a relationship with it where you can, as it were, just accept it just as it is.

167
00:15:46,059 --> 00:15:59,754
Sometimes if you spice your looking, if you spice that investigation with a certain warmth, with a certain loving kindness towards the body, a certain loving kindness towards the mind, that also can be very helpful.

168
00:16:00,054 --> 00:16:00,254
See?

169
00:16:01,456 --> 00:16:08,182
So in the Mahayana they call one Buddha Avalokiteshvara, which means to look down upon with compassion.

170
00:16:08,524 --> 00:16:09,443
So you can do that to yourself.

171
00:16:11,365 --> 00:16:11,986
Give yourself a hug.

172
00:16:13,349 --> 00:16:13,788
Occasionally.

173
00:16:14,782 --> 00:16:22,413
But the purpose is to see and to feel feelings as they really are, all these emotions around aversion and fear.

174
00:16:26,038 --> 00:16:31,047
See, always the same technique, coming off the mind into the body, feeling feelings.

175
00:16:35,192 --> 00:16:42,543
The next one is what my teacher used to call our two very good friends, sloth and torpor, because they're always telling us we need a rest.

176
00:16:44,278 --> 00:16:47,342
We ought to lie down a little bit, and it's all too tough for us.

177
00:16:48,024 --> 00:17:04,127
So, we recognize that, having slept a wonderful sleep, we recognize that any doziness, any torpor in the mind, that sort of heaviness in the head, or that heaviness in the body, all that is to be seen as turbulence.

178
00:17:04,147 --> 00:17:08,994
Now, normally we don't recognize it as that, but it's an energy form, isn't it?

179
00:17:09,595 --> 00:17:14,201
It's an energy form which is actually drawing us down into the pit

180
00:17:15,109 --> 00:17:15,410
Isn't it?

181
00:17:15,951 --> 00:17:17,053
The pit of oblivion.

182
00:17:18,054 --> 00:17:19,836
It wants to squash us out.

183
00:17:21,479 --> 00:17:21,779
Doesn't it?

184
00:17:24,284 --> 00:17:27,468
You just want to lie down and disappear.

185
00:17:27,788 --> 00:17:29,230
See, self-annihilate.

186
00:17:29,912 --> 00:17:31,574
It's a sort of soft suicide.

187
00:17:34,519 --> 00:17:35,820
Just disappear for a while.

188
00:17:36,481 --> 00:17:36,701
See?

189
00:17:37,143 --> 00:17:44,272
So these sloths and torpods, they hide a lot of worms and snakes down there, you see.

190
00:17:45,349 --> 00:17:54,105
Because we've learnt that, you know, one way that we can escape pain, whatever it is, you know, like we just don't get fed up with life or something, is just go to sleep for a while.

191
00:17:54,887 --> 00:17:59,435
And of course you wake up, you feel okay, you feel great, you feel better, you see?

192
00:17:59,717 --> 00:18:01,721
But that sleep has been a suppressant.

193
00:18:01,780 --> 00:18:03,544
It's pushed all that stuff down.

194
00:18:03,805 --> 00:18:05,146
It's an actual force.

195
00:18:06,545 --> 00:18:11,231
I'm sure that sometimes you've actually made the effort, I know I have, to actually go to sleep.

196
00:18:12,212 --> 00:18:15,679
Put your head in the pillow, go to sleep.

197
00:18:15,699 --> 00:18:17,060
Or force yourself into sleep.

198
00:18:20,986 --> 00:18:28,778
And that sort of time when we don't have to get up to go to work or anything, when we don't have to get up, and you sort of wake up and you turn over.

199
00:18:31,481 --> 00:18:33,565
Hours pass, hours pass.

200
00:18:34,404 --> 00:18:35,266
Sweet oblivion.

201
00:18:36,047 --> 00:18:38,911
Well, of course, that is not the enlightenment.

202
00:18:40,492 --> 00:18:44,818
The nirvanic bliss is not annihilation or some sort of total oblivion.

203
00:18:46,741 --> 00:18:59,298
So, recognizing that as a turbulence, our job is again to stay above it, to feel it as feelings, and by doing so, we're actually educating that energy to come upwards instead of downwards.

204
00:18:59,718 --> 00:19:05,584
And what you find, if you stay with it, and some of it can be very heavy, some of it can stay with you a long time.

205
00:19:06,184 --> 00:19:09,288
There's no rule about that.

206
00:19:09,868 --> 00:19:13,792
If you stay with it, you'll see it purifies, and to your surprise, you have more energy.

207
00:19:14,353 --> 00:19:19,337
So many of you who've come on a longer retreat, you know that the first three days are horrible.

208
00:19:20,298 --> 00:19:21,220
But the energy lifts.

209
00:19:21,420 --> 00:19:23,221
The energy lifts as it purifies itself.

210
00:19:23,542 --> 00:19:27,767
And then suddenly, five hours a night, who wants any more than that?

211
00:19:31,612 --> 00:19:36,477
The next one is restlessness.

212
00:19:39,940 --> 00:19:40,820
There's two actually.

213
00:19:40,840 --> 00:19:42,383
It's a sort of catch-all in a sense.

214
00:19:43,344 --> 00:19:48,088
Restlessness and remorse.

215
00:19:48,628 --> 00:19:51,711
It's all that area to do with guilt, remorse, sorrow.

216
00:19:53,994 --> 00:19:59,200
Which makes you feel guilt, dread of consequences, shame, embarrassment.

217
00:20:00,020 --> 00:20:01,382
All those sorts of feelings.

218
00:20:02,054 --> 00:20:04,875
which really are the product of immoral actions.

219
00:20:05,156 --> 00:20:11,201
But not only that, you can feel quite ashamed by just a social gaffe.

220
00:20:11,801 --> 00:20:16,926
There's a lovely case of, I can't remember the name of the nobleman.

221
00:20:20,490 --> 00:20:21,349
It's gone out of my mind.

222
00:20:21,611 --> 00:20:25,953
But in the court of Queen Elizabeth I, he farted.

223
00:20:27,394 --> 00:20:31,638
And it was so embarrassing, he disappeared from court for three or four years.

224
00:20:33,728 --> 00:20:39,654
When he returned, the queen approached him and said, you are welcome to our court, we have forgot the fart.

225
00:20:43,900 --> 00:20:44,259
Wonderful.

226
00:20:44,921 --> 00:20:49,727
See, for three years the poor man was utterly embarrassed.

227
00:20:49,747 --> 00:20:52,809
But you can't call that immoral, it's just a social gaffe, you see.

228
00:20:54,432 --> 00:20:55,212
Lovely story, isn't it?

229
00:20:59,294 --> 00:21:01,319
So again, we have no option.

230
00:21:01,500 --> 00:21:03,566
You can't do anything about it.

231
00:21:03,645 --> 00:21:06,333
You have to suffer the consequences, you see.

232
00:21:06,433 --> 00:21:13,894
And in so doing, of course, you undermine these attitudes which have caused those very states to arise in the first place.

233
00:21:16,522 --> 00:21:20,730
Restlessness is the opposite of sloth, and it basically tells you to move.

234
00:21:20,970 --> 00:21:23,074
You want to get up and get out, do something, you know?

235
00:21:23,815 --> 00:21:26,259
So, sometimes it has no reason.

236
00:21:26,419 --> 00:21:29,202
I mean, it doesn't tell you what it's restless about.

237
00:21:29,243 --> 00:21:30,806
You just feel restless.

238
00:21:32,548 --> 00:21:40,101
In which case, just like sloth and torpor, you've got to sit in the midst of that turbulence, go sit in the midst of the fire, you see, and just feel it.

239
00:21:41,126 --> 00:21:50,036
Often it's a good thing to wander up and down the body, you see, in which case this taking your attention up and down the body has a sort of relaxing effect.

240
00:21:50,537 --> 00:21:56,803
Just watching, just feeling the body going down as it were in a systematic way.

241
00:21:57,364 --> 00:22:02,588
Those of you who've done the U Ba Kin technique with people like the Goenka school will know that.

242
00:22:03,128 --> 00:22:05,392
And it can be very relaxing just to do that.

243
00:22:05,692 --> 00:22:10,576
But again, you're feeling it, you're observing it as a process,

244
00:22:10,861 --> 00:22:17,288
and you're just allowing it to be itself, and eventually the momentum just dies out of energy.

245
00:22:18,530 --> 00:22:20,232
So a lot of this is to do with patience.

246
00:22:20,733 --> 00:22:24,659
And remember the Buddha said patience was the highest form of ascetic practice.

247
00:22:25,519 --> 00:22:25,920
Patience.

248
00:22:26,201 --> 00:22:28,242
It's the ability to suffer, isn't it?

249
00:22:28,262 --> 00:22:30,546
The ability to bear, you see.

250
00:22:31,847 --> 00:22:37,375
And to recognize that this internal environment that we have, you see, it's all been created by us, you know.

251
00:22:39,211 --> 00:22:45,900
It's not as though that our parents and whom we've met and the society hasn't helped to create.

252
00:22:46,540 --> 00:22:47,663
You know, it's been a catalyst.

253
00:22:48,022 --> 00:22:52,689
But it's ourselves who've made these internal decisions that have caused the mind to be like this.

254
00:22:53,369 --> 00:22:58,758
Now, at first, people might think, well, you know, that's a bit much blaming myself.

255
00:22:58,798 --> 00:23:00,039
I should blame all these other people.

256
00:23:00,059 --> 00:23:01,101
You know, they make me suffer.

257
00:23:01,300 --> 00:23:06,248
But if you do that, then you're caught in this idea that you've got to change the world before you can change it.

258
00:23:07,273 --> 00:23:08,536
because they're the ones who are causing it.

259
00:23:08,895 --> 00:23:15,945
But when you recognize that you're the sole cause of your states, then it empowers you to do something about it.

260
00:23:20,313 --> 00:23:23,637
So finally, there's this whole tricky area of doubt.

261
00:23:24,097 --> 00:23:26,521
And doubt's a funny thing.

262
00:23:33,612 --> 00:23:34,834
It's the opposite of faith.

263
00:23:35,454 --> 00:23:37,196
Faith is, in Buddhism...

264
00:23:37,835 --> 00:23:42,039
a trust, a confidence.

265
00:23:48,267 --> 00:23:52,571
It comes from a sort of intellectual thing, an intellectual ascent.

266
00:23:54,034 --> 00:24:00,500
So you've read about Buddhism, you've read about meditation, you've heard about it, you've discussed it and all that.

267
00:24:02,236 --> 00:24:10,915
and there comes a faith, a trust in it, and then you practice, and the practice supports that, and eventually the faith grows, the confidence grows, you see.

268
00:24:12,338 --> 00:24:21,240
It's not just confidence in the teaching, in the vipassana and all that, it's also confidence in yourself to do it.

269
00:24:25,657 --> 00:24:30,002
And sometimes you find yourself undermining yourself by saying, well, I can't do it.

270
00:24:30,083 --> 00:24:31,523
I can't do this and I can't do that.

271
00:24:32,345 --> 00:24:34,186
You have to watch that thought very carefully.

272
00:24:34,768 --> 00:24:35,469
Where's it leading?

273
00:24:36,829 --> 00:24:42,556
It's more in the sense of we should be aware of the way we talk to ourselves and say the opposite.

274
00:24:43,336 --> 00:24:44,919
Yeah, I can.

275
00:24:44,939 --> 00:24:46,760
Who in my head is telling me I can't do it?

276
00:24:49,044 --> 00:24:50,664
We don't have to believe the mind.

277
00:24:51,465 --> 00:24:53,167
For the most part, it's a liar.

278
00:24:53,653 --> 00:24:56,616
He's always telling us things which don't turn out to be true.

279
00:24:57,838 --> 00:25:02,604
So, when he says, you can't do this, who said that?

280
00:25:02,624 --> 00:25:04,705
You don't have to join in.

281
00:25:04,726 --> 00:25:10,251
You don't have to say, this is the same me as... You can be the listener of your own mind.

282
00:25:10,791 --> 00:25:15,958
And so when it's trying to undermine you, you see, you have to listen to it and just let go of it.

283
00:25:18,300 --> 00:25:20,623
Skeptical doubt...

284
00:25:21,817 --> 00:25:25,503
is the inability for a person to commit themselves.

285
00:25:26,986 --> 00:25:29,028
You can't do it, you know, there's a fear there.

286
00:25:30,951 --> 00:25:35,058
And this is probably the greatest hindrance to the whole spiritual practice.

287
00:25:35,700 --> 00:25:44,232
Because you never get down to sit, you never get down to doing it, because you can't leap beyond the fear of committing yourself.

288
00:25:47,317 --> 00:25:47,438
Right?

289
00:25:48,565 --> 00:25:53,913
So again, when that happens, we have to go into the feelings that are surrounding the doubt.

290
00:25:54,595 --> 00:25:58,039
Feelings that are surrounding it, supporting it.

291
00:26:05,913 --> 00:26:09,038
That's not to be confused with what you might call honest doubt.

292
00:26:09,794 --> 00:26:10,414
A wonder.

293
00:26:10,755 --> 00:26:13,460
Because that's what the Buddha actually wants us to cultivate.

294
00:26:13,859 --> 00:26:15,883
He doesn't want us to take his word as fact.

295
00:26:15,943 --> 00:26:17,546
It's not a blind faith.

296
00:26:17,566 --> 00:26:20,830
He wants us to say, ah, okay, well let's see if that's true.

297
00:26:21,030 --> 00:26:23,736
And then to investigate.

298
00:26:23,756 --> 00:26:26,740
Because the pros of enlightenment isn't one of belief.

299
00:26:27,240 --> 00:26:31,768
If you could believe in Nibbana and you then experience Nibbana, it would be simple, wouldn't it?

300
00:26:33,030 --> 00:26:45,251
it's one of direct experience so to have that direct experience then you've got to have the confidence to actually undergo the training see

301
00:26:58,579 --> 00:27:01,931
Sometimes we transfer that onto another person.

302
00:27:01,971 --> 00:27:03,497
What's the word?

303
00:27:04,038 --> 00:27:04,579
Projected.

304
00:27:05,522 --> 00:27:07,008
And we start having doubt in the teacher.

305
00:27:07,269 --> 00:27:08,112
Heaven forbid.

306
00:27:08,794 --> 00:27:10,159
Now, that doesn't mean...

307
00:27:11,117 --> 00:27:15,385
That doesn't mean that the teacher might be wrong.

308
00:27:16,367 --> 00:27:21,557
But you can't believe it just because the mind puts a doubt onto it.

309
00:27:21,717 --> 00:27:23,299
You have to investigate that as well.

310
00:27:23,740 --> 00:27:27,748
So doubt is quite insidious actually.

311
00:27:27,888 --> 00:27:29,211
Be really careful with it.

312
00:27:30,186 --> 00:27:31,190
It slips up on you.

313
00:27:31,853 --> 00:27:37,352
And sometimes you can undermine your own confidence by setting yourself standards which you can't maintain.

314
00:27:37,973 --> 00:27:42,609
So if you say to yourself after this retreat, then of course you'll be all enormously inspired.

315
00:27:43,298 --> 00:27:47,542
You say to yourself, I'm going to now meditate for two hours every morning and two hours in the evening.

316
00:27:48,765 --> 00:27:52,829
And with great intent and real resolution, you're determined to do that.

317
00:27:53,371 --> 00:27:56,454
And tomorrow morning, you feel a bit down.

318
00:27:56,694 --> 00:27:57,375
And you let go of it.

319
00:27:57,715 --> 00:27:58,938
And you say to yourself, I can't do it.

320
00:27:58,958 --> 00:27:59,578
See, I can't do it.

321
00:28:00,200 --> 00:28:01,902
In which case, you've created this huge doubt.

322
00:28:02,942 --> 00:28:03,784
Because you've overstayed.

323
00:28:03,804 --> 00:28:05,326
You've had too much expectation.

324
00:28:06,126 --> 00:28:07,669
And you undermine yourself.

325
00:28:08,002 --> 00:28:09,224
You have to be careful of that too.

326
00:28:09,365 --> 00:28:13,450
It's better to start low and build up than to try and start high and just flop.

327
00:28:14,490 --> 00:28:14,570
See?

328
00:28:22,240 --> 00:28:24,364
So now those are the five hindrances.

329
00:28:25,505 --> 00:28:34,737
And when I say at the end of a sitting, you see, recollect what you're doing or review what you're doing,

330
00:28:34,884 --> 00:28:36,928
Well, you can take one or two of those things.

331
00:28:36,988 --> 00:28:41,192
For instance, supposing a sloth hit you, you see, during that sitting.

332
00:28:42,234 --> 00:28:44,278
Well, then you can ask yourself, what did I do, you see?

333
00:28:44,397 --> 00:28:45,638
So there are various things we can do.

334
00:28:46,220 --> 00:28:50,586
But as soon as we feel that sort of heaviness come on, we can put more energy in the posture.

335
00:28:50,906 --> 00:28:51,527
Did we do that?

336
00:28:53,170 --> 00:28:55,792
And when it gets a bit too heavy, you can open your eyes, just let a bit of light in.

337
00:28:56,314 --> 00:29:00,960
See, did we do that, or did we sort of forget about it and go into sleep?

338
00:29:01,378 --> 00:29:05,644
And then at some point did we have a feeling, well, no, this is getting the better of me, should I stand up?

339
00:29:07,487 --> 00:29:17,381
So it's a case of also developing these skills of how to stay above these hindrances and not get caught up in them.

340
00:29:17,401 --> 00:29:19,943
And that's part of this reflection at the end of a sitting.

341
00:29:20,684 --> 00:29:24,770
And then, you see, what happens is you become wise about yourself.

342
00:29:25,155 --> 00:29:29,540
It's not as though the trick that you employed in the last sitting will work in the next one.

343
00:29:29,780 --> 00:29:32,624
See, the mind's slippery, yeah?

344
00:29:32,644 --> 00:29:34,005
You can't catch it that easy.

345
00:29:34,465 --> 00:29:42,334
But at least we get to know ourselves and we get to know that that fundament, usually what's wrong is that we haven't actually committed ourselves.

346
00:29:42,354 --> 00:29:45,277
We haven't actually given a full commitment to the practice.

347
00:29:45,977 --> 00:29:53,424
And that's why it's so important when you begin any sitting, even if it's only just five minutes in the morning, that just that thought comes to the mind, that right.

348
00:29:53,978 --> 00:30:01,518
From now until the end of the sitting, I'm going to maintain a real effort to stay mindful.

349
00:30:01,538 --> 00:30:10,781
And that's why I like to stress this business of sometime in the early morning to make that determination to remain mindful during the day.

350
00:30:10,821 --> 00:30:17,538
Not to compartmentalize the day.

351
00:30:18,480 --> 00:30:20,626
Not to think that sitting meditation...

